</div></div><div class="sqs-block horizontalrule-block sqs-block-horizontalrule" data-block-type="47" id="block-yui_3_17_2_1_1739201418139_41739"><div class="sqs-block-content"><hr /></div></div><div class="sqs-block html-block sqs-block-html" data-block-type="2" id="block-yui_3_17_2_1_1738344274490_48107"><div class="sqs-block-content">

<div class="sqs-html-content">
  <h1 style="text-align:center;white-space:pre-wrap;">Important Announcement</h1><p class="" style="white-space:pre-wrap;"><strong>January 31, 2025</strong></p><p class="" style="white-space:pre-wrap;">The Board of Directors of Disability Rights Connecticut (DRCT) announces that our current Executive Director, Deborah Dorfman, has resigned effective February 7th to accept a position in Massachusetts leading efforts for systemic reform to better serve individuals with mental illness.&nbsp;We want to thank Debbie for her passion, leadership, legal acumen, and service to individuals with disabilities. She has successfully championed numerous lawsuits, the outcome of which benefit many individuals with disabilities and will lead to important legal reform.</p><p class="" style="white-space:pre-wrap;">As our Board conducts a search for a new Executive Director, we have asked Santina Sciaba-Douglas, current Deputy Executive Director, to serve as Interim Executive Director.&nbsp;The Board of Directors will conduct a nationwide search for a permanent Executive Director.&nbsp;Our process will include input from DRCT staff, board members, community partners, and other stakeholders.</p><p class="" style="white-space:pre-wrap;">The vision of DRCT, Connecticut’s protection and advocacy system, is to utilize a wide array of legal and advocacy strategies and strong relationships with community partners to protect the rights and positively impact the well-being of individuals with disabilities in Connecticut.</p><p style="text-align:justify;white-space: normal !important;white-space:pre-wrap;" class="">Sincerely,</p><p style="text-align:justify;white-space: normal !important;white-space:pre-wrap;" class="">Kathryn du Pree<br>﻿Board President<br>Disability Rights Connecticut</p>
</div>




















  
  



</div></div><div class="sqs-block horizontalrule-block sqs-block-horizontalrule" data-block-type="47" id="block-yui_3_17_2_1_1722290713198_68971"><div class="sqs-block-content"><hr /></div></div><div class="sqs-block html-block sqs-block-html" data-block-type="2" id="block-yui_3_17_2_1_1726760137974_145879"><div class="sqs-block-content">

<div class="sqs-html-content">
  <h1 style="text-align:center;white-space:pre-wrap;"><a href="/osep-complaint-csde" target="_blank"><strong>Complaint Filed with U.S. Department of Education Alleging Significant Deficiencies in Oversight of Education Provided to Connecticut Students with Disabilities</strong></a></h1><p class="" style="white-space:pre-wrap;">Disability Rights Connecticut (DRCT) and the Connecticut Office of the Child Advocate (OCA) on September 18, 2024 filed a Complaint with the U.S. Office of Special Education Programs (OSEP) alleging that despite having “monitoring and regulatory oversight obligations” for “all special education schools and programs” the Connecticut State Department of Education (CSDE) has “not exercised the requisite monitoring and regulatory oversight” of High Road schools in Connecticut, private equity owned segregated schools where multiple school districts place students with disabilities.</p><blockquote><p class="" style="white-space:pre-wrap;">“Based on the findings of our systemic investigation and CSDE’s continued noncompliance with IDEA (Individuals with Disabilities Education Act) oversight and monitoring, OCA and DRCT request that OSEP conduct its own investigation … and issue an appropriate corrective action plan for CSDE based on its findings.”</p></blockquote>
</div>




















  
  



